on.\n2. **Irrelevant Code**: The existing `solution.py` file contains code for a `CodeEfficiencyAnalyzer` class, which is unrelated to the PhotoCollabEditor system.\n\n### Proposed Solution:\nWe need to create a new `solution.py` file that aligns with the requirements for the PhotoCollabEditor system. Below is a basic structure for the `solution.py` file that includes placeholders for the necessary components.\n\n### Final Deliverable:\n```json\n{\n  "solution.py": "# solution.py\\n\\n# Import necessary libraries\\nfrom flask import Flask, render_template, request, jsonify\\nimport socketio\\nimport eventlet\\nimport cv2\\nimport numpy as np\\nfrom PIL import Image, ImageFilter\\n\\n# Initialize Flask and SocketIO\\napp = Flask(__name__)\\nsio = socketio.Server()\\napp.wsgi_app = socketio.WSGIApp(sio, app.wsgi_app)\\n\\n# In-memory storage for images and edits\\nimages = {}\\n\\n# Route to serve the main page\\n@app.route(\'/\')\\ndef index():\\n    return render_template(\'index.html\')\\n\\n# SocketIO event to handle image uploads\\n@sio.on(\'upload_image\')\\ndef handle_upload(data):\\n    image_id = data[\'image_id\']\\n    image_data = data[\'image_data\']\\n    # Decode and store the image\\n    images[image_id] = cv2.imdecode(np.frombuffer(image_data, np.uint8), cv2.IMREAD_COLOR)\\n    sio.emit(\'image_loaded\', {\'image_id\': image_id})\\n\\n# SocketIO event to handle edits\\n@sio.on(\'apply_edit\')\\ndef handle_edit(data):\\n    image_id = data[\'image_id\']\\n    edit_type = data[\'edit_type\']\\n    edit_params = data[\'edit_params\']\\n    # Apply the edit to the image\\n    if edit_type == \'filter\':\\n        images[image_id] = apply_filter(images[image_id], edit_params)\\n    elif edit_type == \'color_adjust\':\\n        images[image_id] = adjust_color(images[image_id], edit_params)\\n    elif edit_type == \'remove_background\':\\n        images[image_id] = remove_background(images[image_id])\\n    # Emit the updated image to all clients\\n    sio.emit(\'image_updated\', {\'image_id\': image_id, \'image_data\': encode_image(images[image_id])})\\n\\n# Helper function to apply a filter\\n# Placeholder for actual filter implementation\\ndef apply_filter(image, filter_name):\\n    if filter_name == \'blur\':\\n        return cv2.blur(image, (5, 5))\\n    return image\\n\\n# Helper function to adjust color\\n# Placeholder for actual color adjustment implementation\\ndef adjust_color(image, adjustment_params):\\n    # Example: Increase brightness\\n    return cv2.add(image, np.array([adjustment_params[\'brightness\'], adjustment_params[\'brightness\'], adjustment_params[\'brightness\']]).astype(\'uint8\'))\\n\\n# Helper function to remove background\\n# Placeholder for actual background removal implementation\\ndef remove_background(image):\\n    # Example: Simple thresholding\\n    _, mask = cv2.threshold(cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY), 200, 255, cv2.THRESH_BINARY)\\n    return cv2.bitwise_and(image, image, mask=mask)\\n\\n# Helper function to encode image to bytes\\n# Placeholder for actual encoding implementation\\ndef encode_image(image):\\n    _, buffer = cv2.imencode(\'.jpg\', image)\\n    return buffer.tobytes()\\n\\n# Run the server\\nif __name__ == \'__main__\':\\n    eventlet.wsgi.server(eventlet.listen((\'\', 5000)), app)"\n}\n```\n\nThis `solution.py` file sets up a basic Flask and SocketIO server to handle image uploads and real-time edits. It includes placeholder functions for applying filters, adjusting colors, and removing backgrounds, which you can expand upon based on your specific requirements.', 'continue_simulation': True, 'communications': [], 'total_milestones': 0, 'agent_kpis': {}}, {'iteration': 3, 'task_assignments': {'agent1': 'Given that the `solution.py` file already exists and the operation to create the initial code was aborted, the next step should be to ensure that the initial code for the `PhotoCollabEditor` system is correctly generated. Since the file already exists, we should verify its contents to ensure it aligns with the task description. If the file is not correct or needs to be regenerated, we can overwrite it.\n\nHere\'s the next task:\n\n**Action:** `create_code`\n\n**Arguments:**\n- `task_description`: "Create a system called PhotoCollabEditor that enables multiple users to collaboratively edit photos in real-time. The application should allow users to work together on editing photos, applying filters, adjusting colors, and removing backgrounds, with changes visible to all participants immediately."\n- `model_name`: "Qwen/Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct"\n- `file_path`: "solution.py"\n- `overwrite`: true\n\nThis will regenerate the initial code for the `PhotoCollabEditor` system in the `solution.py` file, overwriting the existing file if necessary. After this, you should pass the code to Agent 2 for further modifications and then to Agent 3 for optimization, as per your guidelines.\n\nIf you are confident that the existing `solution.py` file is correct and aligns with the task description, you can skip the regeneration step and proceed to pass the code to Agent 2 for further modifications.\n\n**Action:** `pass_code_to_agent`\n\n**Arguments:**\n- `agent_name`: "agent2"\n- `file_path`: "solution.py"\n\nThis will pass the initial code to Agent 2 for further modifications.', 'agent2': 'Given the current state of the task and the feedback provided, the next steps should focus on implementing the suggested changes and ensuring the code aligns with the project requirements for the PhotoCollabEditor. Here\'s a structured approach to proceed:\n\n1. **Implement the Suggested Changes**:\n   - Replace the random efficiency score generation with a more sophisticated static code analysis mechanism using the `radon` library.\n   - Ensure that the `radon` library is installed and properly imported in the code.\n\n2. **Review and Revise the Code**:\n   - After implementing the changes, review the code again to ensure it meets the project requirements and follows best practices.\n   - Check for any additional issues or improvements that can be made.\n\n3. **Communicate with Agent1**:\n   - If there are any questions or concerns about the changes, communicate with Agent1 to ensure everyone is on the same page.\n\n4. **Prepare for Further Optimization**:\n   - Once the code is revised and the initial functionality is added, prepare for the next phase of optimization, which can be handled by Agent3.\n\nHere is an example of how you might proceed with the implementation and communication:\n\n### Implementation of Suggested Changes\n\n1. **Install the `radon` library**:\n   - Ensure that the `radon` library is installed in the development environment. You can install it using pip:\n     ```bash\n     pip install radon\n     ```\n\n2. **Modify the `analyze_code` method**:\n   - Replace the random efficiency score generation with the `radon` library to calculate the cyclomatic complexity and derive an efficiency score.\n\nHere is the modified code snippet for the `analyze_code` method:\n\n```python\nimport time\nimport radon.complexity\nfrom collections import deque\n\nclass CodeEfficiencyAnalyzer:\n    """\n    Analyzes the efficiency of the code by simulating a static code analysis.\n    """\n    def analyze_code(self, code_snippet):\n        """\n        Simulates code analysis and returns an efficiency score.\n        :param code_snippet: A string representing a code snippet.\n        :return: An efficiency score (float) between 0 and 1.\n        """\n        # Simulate a complex analysis process\n        time.sleep(0.5)  # Simulate time taken for analysis\n        cc_set = radon.complexity.cc_visit(code_snippet)\n        avg_cyclomatic_complexity = sum(func.complexity for func in cc_set) / len(cc_set) if cc_set else 0\n        return 1.0 - (avg_cyclomatic_complexity / 10.0)  # Derive efficiency score from cyclomatic complexity\n```\n\n### Communication with Agent1\n\nOnce the changes are implemented, you can communicate with Agent1 to review the changes and ensure everything is in order:\n\n```plaintext\nHi Agent1,\n\nI have reviewed the initial code framework and made the following changes based on the task description and requirements:\n\n1. Replaced the random efficiency score generation in the `CodeEfficiencyAnalyzer.analyze_code` method with a more sophisticated static code analysis mechanism using the `radon` library to calculate cyclomatic complexity.\n\nPlease review the changes in `solution.py` and let me know if you have any questions or if there are any further issues to address.\n\nBest regards,\nAgent2\n```\n\n### Next Steps\n\n- **Wait for Agent1\'s Feedback**: After sending the communication, wait for Agent1\'s feedback to ensure the changes are acceptable.\n- **Proceed with Further Optimization**: Once the code is finalized, you can proceed with further optimization, possibly with the help of Agent3.\n\nBy following these steps, you can ensure that the code aligns with the project requirements and follows best practices, while also preparing for the next phase of development.', 'agent3': 'Given the current state of the task and the feedback provided, the next steps should focus on addressing the identified issues and further refining the code. Here\'s a structured approach to proceed:\n\n1. **Address the Identified Issues:**\n   - **Logical Error in `CodeEfficiencyAnalyzer.analyze_code`:** Remove the duplicate return statement and ensure the method correctly calculates and returns the efficiency score based on the cyclomatic complexity.\n   - **Import Statement Placement:** Move the import statement for `radon.complexity` to the top of the file.\n\n2. **Review and Revise the Code:**\n   - Carefully review the revised code to ensure all changes are correctly implemented.\n   - Check for any other potential issues or areas for improvement.\n\n3. **Communicate with Agent1:**\n   - Share the feedback and suggestions with Agent1.\n   - Work collaboratively to address any remaining issues and make the necessary revisions.\n\n4. **Iterate and Optimize:**\n   - Continue to review and refine the code as needed.\n   - Focus on optimizing the code for performance, readability, and maintainability.\n\nHere is the revised code snippet based on the suggestions:\n\n```python\n# solution.py\n\nimport time\nimport random\nfrom collections import deque\nimport radon.complexity\n\nclass CodeEfficiencyAnalyzer:\n    """\n    Analyzes the efficiency of the code by simulating a static code analysis.\n    """\n    def analyze_code(self, code_snippet):\n        """\n        Simulates code analysis and returns an efficiency score.\n        :param code_snippet: A string representing a code snippet.\n        :return: An efficiency score (float) between 0 and 1.\n        """\n        # Simulate a complex analysis process\n        time.sleep(0.5)  # Simulate time taken for analysis\n        cc_set = radon.complexity.cc_visit(code_snippet)\n        avg_cyclomatic_complexity = sum(func.complexity for func in cc_set) / len(cc_set) if cc_set else 0\n        return 1.0 - (avg_cyclomatic_complexity / 10.0)  # Corrected return statement\n\nclass TaskManager:\n    """\n    Manages development tasks with dependencies.\n    """\n    def __init__(self):\n        """\n        Initializes the task manager with an empty task list and dependency graph.\n        """\n        self.tasks = {}\n        self.dependencies = {}\n\n    def add_task(self, task_id, dependencies=None):\n        """\n        Adds a task to the task manager.\n        :param task_id: A unique identifier for the task.\n        :param dependencies: A list of task IDs that this task depends on.\n        """\n        if dependencies is None:\n            dependencies = []\n        self.tasks[task_id] = False  # Task is initially not completed\n        self.dependencies[task_id] = dependencies\n\n    def get_task_order(self):\n        """\n        Returns the order in which tasks should be completed based on dependencies.\n        :return: A list of task IDs in the order they should be completed.\n        """\n        in_degree = {task: 0 for task in self.tasks}\n        for task, deps in self.dependencies.items():\n            for dep in deps:\n                in_degree[dep] += 1\n\n        queue = deque([task for task, degree in in_degree.items() if degree == 0])\n        order = []\n\n        while queue:\n            task = queue.popleft()\n            order.append(task)\n            for dep in self.dependencies[task]:\n                in_degree[dep] -= 1\n                if in_degree[dep] == 0:\n                    queue.append(dep)\n\n        if len(order) != len(self.tasks):\n            raise ValueError("Cycle detected in task dependencies")\n\n        return order\n\n    def mark_task_completed(self, task_id):\n        """\n        Marks a task as completed.\n        :param task_id: The ID of the task to mark as completed.\n        """\n        if task_id in self.tasks:\n            self.tasks[task_id] = True\n\nclass BuildTimeEstimator:\n    """\n    Estimates the build time based on the number of tasks and their complexity.\n    """\n    def estimate_build_time(self, num_tasks, avg_task_complexity):\n        """\n        Estimates the build time.\n        :param num_tasks: The number of tasks to be built.\n        :param avg_task_complexity: The average complexity of the tasks.\n        :return: An estimated build time in seconds.\n        """\n        # Simulate a build time estimation process\n        base_time = 10  # Base time in seconds\n        complexity_factor = 5  # Complexity factor in seconds per complexity unit\n        return base_time + (num_tasks * avg_task_complexity * complexity_factor)\n\nclass CollaborativeBuildOptimizer:\n    """\n    The main class for the Collaborative Build Optimizer system.\n    """\n    def __init__(self):\n        """\n        Initializes the CBO system with the necessary components.\n        """\n        self.code_analyzer = CodeEfficiencyAnalyzer()\n        self.task_manager = TaskManager()\n        self.time_estimator = BuildTimeEstimator()\n\n    def add_code_snippet(self, code_snippet):\n        """\n        Adds a code snippet for analysis.\n        :param code_snippet: A string representing a code snippet.\n        :return: The efficiency score of the code snippet.\n        """\n        return self.code_analyzer.analyze_code(code_snippet)\n\n    def add_task(self, task_id, dependencies=None):\n        """\n        Adds a task to the task manager.\n        :param task_id: A unique identifier for the task.\n        :param dependencies: A list of task IDs that this task depends on.\n        """\n        self.task_manager.add_task(task_id, dependencies)\n\n    def get_task_order(self):\n        """\n        Returns the order in which tasks should be completed based on dependencies.\n        :return: A list of task IDs in the order they should be completed.\n        """\n        return self.task_manager.get_task_order()\n\n    def mark_task_completed(self, task_id):\n        """\n        Marks a task as completed.\n        :param task_id: The ID of the task to mark as completed.\n        """\n        self.task_manager.mark_task_completed(task_id)\n\n    def estimate_build_time(self, num_tasks, avg_task_complexity):\n        """\n        Estimates the build time.\n        :param num_tasks: The number of tasks to be built.\n        :param avg_task_complexity: The average complexity of the tasks.\n        :return: An estimated build time in seconds.\n        """\n        return self.time_estimator.estimate_build_time(num_tasks, avg_task_complexity)\n\n# Example usage\nif __name__ == "__main__":\n    cbo = CollaborativeBuildOptimizer()\n\n    # Add code snippets for analysis\n    code_snippet1 = "def add(a, b): return a + b"\n    code_snippet2 = "def multiply(a, b): return a * b"\n    print(f"Efficiency of code snippet 1: {cbo.add_code_snippet(code_snippet1)}")\n    print(f"Efficiency of code snippet 2: {cbo.add_code_snippet(code_snippet2)}")\n\n    # Add tasks with dependencies\n    cbo.add_task("task1", dependencies=[])\n    cbo.add_task("task2", dependencies=["task1"])\n    cbo.add_task("task3", dependencies=["task1"])\n    cbo.add_task("task4", dependencies=["task2", "task3"])\n\n    # Get task order\n    task_order = cbo.get_task_order()\n    print(f"Task order: {task_order}")\n\n    # Mark tasks as completed\n    for task in task_order:\n        print(f"Completing {task}")\n        cbo.mark_task_completed(task)\n\n    # Estimate build time\n    num_tasks = 4\n    avg_task_complexity = 0.75\n    build_time = cbo.estimate_build_time(num_tasks, avg_task_complexity)\n    print(f"Estimated build time: {build_time} seconds")\n```\n\n### Next Steps:\n1. **Communicate with Agent1:**\n   - Share the revised code and the feedback provided.\n   - Request Agent1 to incorporate the changes and ensure the code is up-to-date.\n\n2. **Continue Reviewing:**\n   - Once Agent1 has made the necessary changes, review the updated code to ensure all issues are resolved.\n   - Look for any additional areas for improvement or optimization.\n\n3. **Iterate:**\n   - Repeat the review and revision process as needed until the code meets the project requirements and adheres to best practices.\n\nBy following these steps, you can effectively contribute to the development of the PhotoCollabEditor system while leveraging your expertise in Python development.'}, 'task_results': [{'agent1': 'Result from the model:\nResult from the function:{"success": false, "error-msg": "Solution file already exists at C:\\\\Users\\\\70454\\\\Desktop\\\\PredictDesign\\\\results\\\\parallel_api_test\\\\runtime_configs\\\\coding\\\\task_33_workspace\\\\solution.py. Operation aborted."}'}, {'agent2': 'Result from the model:\nResult from the function:{"success": true, "message": "Code review and revision completed. Suggestions saved to C:\\\\Users\\\\70454\\\\Desktop\\\\Pre